Since, the photo-stability of carbon dots is vital characteristic in bio-imaging of cells, the emission behavior of the GT and GT/chitosan based carbon dots was studied under sun light for 15days (Fig. 2
                     ). As can be seen in Fig. 2 during this period of time the photo-bleaching of the GT/chitosan based carbon dots was not occurred while an enhancement in florescence intensity was observed. This observation can be due to the existence of a complex of GT and chitosan carbon dots that release fresh dots after erosion of shells one. An experimental confirmation of this conversation is the increase in the viscosity of carbon-dot solution over time (Fig. 3
                     ), which can be due to its erosion. During seven days exposure of samples at continuous light illumination, the fluorescence intensity of the GT based carbon dots is remained constant and after 7days, a 10% decrease of the fluorescence intensity was observed. Finally, during illumination experiment no fluorescence decrease was observed for GT/chitosan based carbon dots. Again a slightly decreasing in fluorescence intensity was observed for GT based carbon dots and hence it can be concluded the bio-polymer based carbon dots provides excellent photo-stability.

The particle size (hydrodynamic diameter) of the prepared carbon dots from both the GT and GT/chitosan gel was estimated by using dynamic light scattering (DLS) technique. An average particle size of GT and GT/chitosan based carbon dots are 170 and 150nm, respectively. Moreover, AFM image (Fig. 4
                     ) exhibits that the GT and GT/chitosan based carbon dots are mono-disperse and spherical. The precise size of nanoparticles in full detail was obtained using TEM imaging. As is clear from Fig. 5
                     , final nanoparticles are 70 to 90nm particles composed of less than 20nm carbon dots. The zeta potential (ζ) is a main parameter which applied for the prediction of the stability of nanoparticles in solutions [36]. The GT based carbon dots has a negative zeta potential (−23.6mV) as a results of the carboxylic surface functional groups and the zeta potential for GT/chitosan based carbon dots was found to be +31.3mV owing to the existence of amino surface functional groups. The large values of the zeta potential indicate a stable colloid system.

As observed in (Fig. 9
                     ), the absorption spectrum of the GT based carbon dots reveals a single peak at 278nm. In the absorption spectrum of the GT/chitosan based carbon dots two peaks located on 250 and 280nm were observed. These peaks centered on 250–300nm showing then n–σ*, n–π* and π–π* transitions an further confirms the presence, CN, CO and CC surface functional groups in the bio-polymer based carbon dots [19,24]. As shown in voltammograms (Fig. 10
                     ), the same electrochemical behavior of GT/chitosan based carbon dots were observed in comparison with GT alone but the current values for GT/chitosan based carbon dots were higher which indicates the higher electro activity for GT/chitosan based carbon dots. Also, it can be seen that there is only one oxidation peak at 0.3V for the CV curve of GT/chitosan based carbon dots.

To investigate the potential of GT and GT/chitosan based carbon dots for bio-imaging application; the cytotoxicity of them was evaluated on HUVEC cell line using MTT assays. The viability of cells was evaluated after 24h of exposure to different concentrations of the as-prepared carbon dots. As shown in the (Fig. 11
                        ) both GT and GT/chitosan based carbon dots were not able to induce cytotoxicity in HUVEC normal cell line, up to concentration of 50μg/ml. Moreover, fluorescence microscopy images after 4h incubation with synthesized carbon dots showed almost every cell was stained blue with clear cell borders, indicating a very effective uptake of fluorescent nanoparticles. It can be noticed that GT and GT/chitosan based carbon dots provides exceptional biocompatibility and can act as a safe probe for biological in vivo applications. It should be noted that cellular cell wall has a negative charge. As presented in (Fig. 12
                        ), due to the positively charged GT/chitosan based carbon dots which determined by zeta-potential measurements, these carbon dots were introduced into the cell walls directly. But in the case of the GT based carbon dots the repulsion between the negatively charged carbon dots and cell walls leads to these nanoparticles did not pass through the cell wall barrier. Since the GT/chitosan based carbon dots can be efficiently internalized through the cells, they can be used as the potent candidates for the intra-cellular imaging. Also the GT based carbon dots can be exploited for extra-cellular imaging and is particularly interesting for in vivo inter-plasma applications.
